(2 comments)

Looks good. Do you have a "Tested:" footer here, which could tell us how this has been tested? Do you have a sample log, so that we can see what the log looks like in action? You can use a GitHub Gist as a pastebin to paste in a large amount of text.
Test log added.
Additionally, there were other test cases performed (with different log outputs), which, however, were not recorded down, and is not repeatable at the moment, as I'm in China now..
Can you add these to the other TODO when you get back from China?
No worries! I also plan to develop an integration test in addition to the unit test, which was added in the TODO list of the bug.
Suggested wording: "The sensor has failed with a critical issue."
Done

Can this feature be disabled at compile time, if the failsafe logger feature is not wanted? It looks like it could be CPU intensive in certain situations. Perhaps a Meson compile-time option for this?

Also, what is the significance of the magic number 20?

The number 20 is exactly to limit the resource usage here, which will limit the number of logs output per second in each zone. Using 20 here would limit the output rate to be no larger than 100 for most platforms as the number of zones are usually <=3.

According to Nan, this feature should be normally enabled, since checking out the detailed reason regarding failsafe mode (dis-)enabling would be quite troublesome for the otherwise, which is also quite commonly happening.
The above is a great comment. Can you put it in the code? That way, other people will also not be surprised about the magic number 20.
Done
Suggested wording: "The sensor timed out."
Done

These headers were added, which is good, but what about actual unit tests for this new feature of failsafe logging? Please add a unit test for it, as this feature appears to be a non-trivial addition, as there's a decent amount of code contained in this changelist.

Discussed with Nan, I'm adding the TODOs in another bug, which will be raised to P0 after I submit this update, so that I'll get to them immediately when back: The TODOs are not functionally critical, but are mostly (very-)nice-to-have features.

More specifically, I'm traveling internationally and have no access for testing, so I'd prefer some changes not to be applied at this time, for safety.

Nevertheless, both the unit test and integration test are added in the TODOs. I hope the manual test log in the description would suffice for now.
OK, makes sense. What's here is a good checkpoint of the work so far.
